net.cloud.gfx.handlers

Class MouseEventHandler

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.awt.event.MouseAdapter
      • net.cloud.gfx.handlers.MouseEventHandler
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.awt.event.MouseListener, java.awt.event.MouseMotionListener, java.awt.event.MouseWheelListener, java.util.EventListener

    public class MouseEventHandler
extends java.awt.event.MouseAdapter
    This MouseAdapter will listen for mouse events in general and take events the Element hierarchy is interested in and pass them on to the quasi-root Interface. It will also take care of starting and stopping drag events on element that are pressed.

      • MouseEventHandler

        public MouseEventHandler(RootPanel rootPanel,
                         Interface elementRoot)
        Create a MouseEventHandler which will hand the events it receives off to the given Interface. Only the events which Elements are interested in, of course.
        Parameters:
        rootPanel - The root panel. Needed so a click may request focus changes to the panel.
        elementRoot - The Interface which is at the top of the element hierarchy

    • Method Detail

      • mousePressed

        public void mousePressed(java.awt.event.MouseEvent event)
        The mouse was pressed. This is how some elements react, and how dragging starts. We only care about left presses, this is a simplifying assumption. Will create and register a drag handler for whatever element the mouse was pressed on.
        Specified by:

      • topElement

        private Element topElement(java.awt.Point eventPoint)
        Find the top element for an event. Will try even if an exception occurs, so that the returned Element is not null. Use this result soon, or it could soon be invalidated.
        Parameters:
        eventPoint - The point of the mouse event. Translated by return time.
        Returns:
        The Element showing on top of the rest at the point

      • currentIsModal

        private boolean currentIsModal()
        Assumes a check has been made and a modal dialog is present. Check to see if the current focused object is the modal dialog, or a child of the modal dialog. If the current focused object is not an Element, then this will simply return false.
        Returns:
        True if the currently focused object is within scope of the modal dialog
